args: Thank you all for coming to see the\nchildren's performance today.
They've all worked very hard for this day,\nso please, enjoy the show!
Eve looks really nervous.\nYou think she'll be okay?
I don't know; she still doesn't have many\nfriends she's comfortable with.
＂I...I a-always believed y-you would come\nfor me, P-P-Prince...＂
Oh man, ouch. That ain't good.
Thankfully, the number of harsh theater\ncritics at a children's performance is\nlikely to be quite low.
＂Nothing is too much for you,\nmy beloved. Please take this\nas a token of my affection.＂
It must have degraded after being in the\norphanage's storage for so long.
Never mind the tiara—this PLAY will fall\napart if we don't do something!
Now I can't be a princess...
I knew I could never be a pri—
＂I have been watching over you for an age,\nand I know you deserve happiness.＂
＂You should never belittle yourself thus.\nNow, bow your head and accept\nthis crown.＂
＂I am a saint who has come to\nbestow an oracle upon you.＂
＂This tiara is a gift from the goddess,\nand I have come to give it—\nand her words—to you, Princess.＂
This play is getting WEIRD, man.
That's why we couldn't find her earlier.\nShe was changing into her dress and\ntracking down a spare tiara.
And thanks to her, this little play is\ngonna go out with a happy endin'!
You're right, Ranzal—look how happy\nall the children on stage are!
＂Now take this crown and wear it\non your head with pride!＂
I don't know how they stuck that landin',\nbut they stuck it GOOD!
Magnificent work, everyone! Bravo!\nWell? What did you think of acting?
Umm, I...I didn't do very well. But...
But you came to save me.\nJust like the goddess.
When you saved me, you were so pretty\nand nice and...
And you were JUST like the goddess!\nThank you, ma'am!
Hildegarde? Oh, there ya are!\nC'mon, we gotta shake a leg or...
I think I may have been right after all.
Prayer used to be my entire life.\nI spent my every waking moment\nbegging the goddess for salvation.
But looking back on it, perhaps that\nwasn't such a bad thing after all.
I believe that all of those prayers\nwere leading up to this moment.
It led to me meeting all of you,\nsaving others, and being able to grow.
Now I am not the one being saved—\nI am the one DOING the saving.
I'm sure you were all along.
Right? Heck, you've helped all of us!
That saint act of yers was PERFECT!\nIt's almost like ya practiced it.
Most certainly not! ...However, it is fair\nto say this is not the first time I have\nplayed the role of a saint.
Not the first time? You mean...
You see it now. The role I was given as\na child wasn't the princess—it was the\nsaint who confers the goddess's words.
Ha! Talk about casting to type!
I suppose it was a perfect role for me—\nor it is now, given how my life went.
Back then, I wanted to be a princess more\nthan I wanted to be a saint.
But now, I feel as though the role\nof a saint suits me better.
I was right to believe that prayers\nbring salvation to people, and that\nthe goddess watches over us always.
(My loneliness and prayers led me here.\nI didn't know it then, but I'm sure I was\npraying to meet all of my new friends.)
(Oh, Goddess. My most heartfelt thanks\nfor allowing me to meet them.)
(And as I keep working to make my dreams\ncome true, please watch over me.)
(I may be praying in a different way,\nbut prayer is still everything to me.)
